Blow and Drive Interlock - Wikipedia





















 






Blow and Drive Interlock

From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia


					Jump to:					navigation, 					search


Blow & Drive Interlock, Corp.


Type

Public


Traded as
OTCQB: BDIC


Industry
Manufacturing


Founded
2013 (2013)


Headquarters
Los Angeles, California, United States



Key people

Laurence Wainer
(President, Chief Executive Officer and Director)[1][2]
Abraham Summers
(Chief Financial Officer)[1][2][3]


Website
www.blowanddrive.com


Blow & Drive Interlock, based in Los Angeles, California, is a publicly traded company that manufactures, distributes, and leases its Ignition Interlock Device Model# BDI-747 across 11 States in the United States of America.[4][5][6][7]



Contents


1 The BDI-747
2 Regulatory Approvals
3 Recent Developments
4 References
5 External links



The BDI-747[edit]
The BDI-747 is a state of the art ignition interlock device, breath-alcohol testing device approximately the size of a smartphone. The ignition interlock device requires the driver to exhale into the device prior to starting the vehicle. The device will prevent the vehicle from starting if the driver's blood-alcohol content exceeds a predetermined set level. It is the only wireless, digital, touchscreen, GPS-enabled, ignition interlock device to comply with the 2013 NHTSA guidelines.
Interlocks may be required for use by DUI or DWI ("driving under the influence" or "driving while intoxicated") offenders as part of their mandatory court or motor vehicle department program. The individual subject to the court or motor vehicle order pays for the installation/removal and monthly lease of the ignition interlock device. Blow & Drive Interlock provides services relating to monitoring of the device at predetermined intervals according to state guidelines. Data is then collected and made available to the appropriate authorities for review.
The Company's principal location is in Los Angeles County, California and has over 100 qualified personnel to install, calibrate, remove and monitor the devices across the eleven U.S. states where it has received approvals to operate. The Company's business plan includes growth of the Company by continuing to complete and submit state applications and to build up its service infrastructure by utilizing its own retail infrastructure, independent installers, distributors and franchisees.[3][8][9][10][11][12][4]
Regulatory Approvals[edit]
Blow & Drive Interlock received U.S. Federal certification from the National Highway and Transportation Safety Administration to provide criminal monitoring services by means of its BDI-747 Breath Alcohol Ignition Interlock Device in 2014. It has since received U.S. State approvals to provide services in conjunction with the judiciary or administrative arms in eleven states since it began formally leasing devices in 2015:[13][14][15][16][17][18][19]

California

Oregon

New York

Pennsylvania

Colorado

Kentucky

Oklahoma

Tennessee

Arizona

Texas

Kansas


Recent Developments[edit]
In September 2016 Blow & Drive Interlock entered into a letter of intent with The Doheny Group to finance an expansion to quadruple the company's market share from its supply of 500 machines to 2,100 machines but then in November announced it was in fact increasing funding to expand the company’s marketshare to 2,700 machines to meet high demand. In a January 2017 filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission, the company reported that it had scaled up production and increased its inventory by approximately 75% to over 2,000 machines and was still on track to meet the 2,700 goal by the end of that fiscal quarter. The company announced it had completed production and deployment reaching this 2,700-machine goal in March 2017 as well as beginning the production process of a further additional 1,000 units, which would bring its total machine-count to 3,700.[20][21][22][23][24]
The company participated with Mothers Against Drunk Driving as a data provider in their MADD 2017 Ignition Interlock Report. The report estimated that 2.3 million attempts to drive drunk had been prevented by ignition interlock legislation since 2006. Over 350,000 driving attempts were stopped in 2016 alone. According to the National Transportation Administration's Department's Office of Behavioral Research, each of these drivers would have had an estimated 6.75x greater chance of crash risk.[25] According to MADD's report, "Every state in the nation has an ignition interlock law of some kind. MADD's goal is for every state to have the most effective ignition interlock law, which is one that applies to every drunk driver after the first offense. When MADD's Campaign started, only New Mexico had an all-offender ignition interlock law. Today, 28 states and the District of Columbia require ignition interlocks for offenders with a .08 blood alcohol concentration (BAC) and above after the first offense. MADD is committed to working with the other 22 states to pass similar laws, and to help every state optimize its laws and expand the use of technology to stop the tragedies caused by drunk driving." [26]
In April 2017, Equities.com did a feature on Blow and Drive's expansion into the state of Texas and how the state is a key for the company as there is a huge market with high demand for its product. The article also highlighted research from Bloomberg and Forbes stating that the potential implications of MADD's proposed legislation will result in the ignition interlock industry exponentially expanding and reaching $1.1 billion to $3.2 billion as early as years 2018-2020.[27][28] The article states that Blow and Drive intends to have over 10,000 ignition interlock devices leased and generating revenue by year-end 2017. The company has increased leased units from December 2016 to March of this year by 145%.[29]
