Blow & Drive Interlock, based in Los Angeles, California, is a publicly traded company that manufactures, distributes, and leases its Ignition Interlock Device Model# BDI-747 across 11 States in the United States of America.[4][5][6][7]



Contents


1 The BDI-747
2 Regulatory Approvals
3 Recent Developments
4 References
5 External links



The BDI-747[edit]
The BDI-747 is a state of the art ignition interlock device, breath-alcohol testing device approximately the size of a smartphone. The ignition interlock device requires the driver to exhale into the device prior to starting the vehicle. The device will prevent the vehicle from starting if the driver's blood-alcohol content exceeds a predetermined set level. It is the only wireless, digital, touchscreen, GPS-enabled, ignition interlock device to comply with the 2013 NHTSA guidelines.
Interlocks may be required for use by DUI or DWI ("driving under the influence" or "driving while intoxicated") offenders as part of their mandatory court or motor vehicle department program. The individual subject to the court or motor vehicle order pays for the installation/removal and monthly lease of the ignition interlock device. Blow & Drive Interlock provides services relating to monitoring of the device at predetermined intervals according to state guidelines. Data is then collected and made available to the appropriate authorities for review.
The Company's principal location is in Los Angeles County, California and has over 100 qualified personnel to install, calibrate, remove and monitor the devices across the eleven U.S. states where it has received approvals to operate. The Company's business plan includes growth of the Company by continuing to complete and submit state applications and to build up its service infrastructure by utilizing its own retail infrastructure, independent installers, distributors and franchisees.[3][8][9][10][11][12][4]
Regulatory Approvals[edit]
Blow & Drive Interlock received U.S. Federal certification from the National Highway and Transportation Safety Administration to provide criminal monitoring services by means of its BDI-747 Breath Alcohol Ignition Interlock Device in 2014. It has since received U.S. State approvals to provide services in conjunction with the judiciary or administrative arms in eleven states since it began formally leasing devices in 2015:[13][14][15][16][17][18][19]

